# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-nesmeyanov
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] An **academician** is a full member of an artistic, literary, engineering, or scientific academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In many countries, it is an honorific title used to denote a full member of an academy that has a strong influence on national scientific life.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Accordingly, within systems such as the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, the title grants privileges and administrative responsibilities for funding allocation and research priorities.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Being an academician in China is a top honour and title granted only to the nation's top scientists and engineers.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Academicians are elected through either the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Chinese Academy of Engineering.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] The British honours "Fellow of the Royal Society" (FRS) or Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences can be considered rough equivalents.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Fellowship of the Academy of Social Sciences was known as the Award of Academician until July 2014.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering in the UK are recognized as academicians and members include Nobel Prize winners and the nation's top engineers and scientists.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Recently, Nobel Prize winner Frances Arnold was elected to the Royal Academy of Engineering.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In the United States of America, academicians are elected members of the National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Engineering.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Members include many Nobel Prize, Turing Awards, and Fields Medalists.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Sweden does not use the Academician concept, but membership in learned societies are noted in the Swedish State Calendar.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] The Swedish Royal Academies are independent organizations, founded on Royal command, that act to promote the arts, culture, and science in Sweden.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] The Swedish Academy and Academy of Sciences who are responsible for the selection of Nobel Prize laureates in Literature, Physics, Chemistry, and the Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Also included in the Royal Academies are scientific societies that were granted Royal Charters.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] There are a few esteemed Swedish learned societies that has not sought Royal command, including the Society of Sciences in Lund.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Academician may also be a functional title and denote a full member of the National Academy of Sciences in those countries where the academy has a strong influence on national scientific life, particularly countries that were part of, or influenced by, the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In such countries, academician is used as an honorific title (like "Doctor", "Professor", etc.) when addressing or speaking about someone.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] However, since the reforms of late USSR dismantled the de facto monopoly of the state on forming academies, the creation of voluntary academies has been allowed.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Therefore, it became customary and almost compulsory to list which academy gave the title to assert its meaningfulness.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In Europe, academicians are elected by Pan-European academies, such as the European Academy of Sciences and Arts and the Academia Europaea.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In Canada, fellowship of the Royal Society of Canada is a comparable honour.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In Finland, "Academician" (Finnish: *akateemikko*, Swedish: *akademiker*) is an honorary title and the President of the Republic nominates the Academicians.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] There can be 12 Finnish Academicians representing science and scholarly pursuits and eight Academicians representing fine arts and literature at the same time.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] The Academy of Finland is the state funding agency of Finnish science and letters, but it has no organizational connection to Finnish Academicians.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] The scientists and scholars funded by the Academy of Finland are called Academy Professors (Finnish: *akatemiaprofessori*, Swedish: *akademiprofessor*) and Academy Research Fellows (Finnish: *akatemiatutkija*, Swedish: *akademiforskare*).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In addition to Academy of Finland, Finland has four independent national academies.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Finnish academies are less recognized globally due to its lack of international exposure and use of English language.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] In Taiwan, elected members of *Academia Sinica* are considered academicians.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] A related option of membership also exists in some countries—a *Corresponding Member* is a person who is eminent in respect of scientific results but cannot or does not wish to become a full academy member.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] One of the reasons for this may be that they live far from the academy and it is inconvenient to often travel to its headquarters.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] It is, for example, the case when the person is not a resident in the country which the academy belongs to.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] For communication, such a scientist uses "correspondence".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Another possible reason is that the charter or traditions of the academy do not admit election of a person to a full membership, unless they have been a corresponding member for a certain period and has demonstrated additional achievements within this period.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academician] Because of this, in the Russian Academy of Sciences a corresponding membership is a seen as a lower level of membership as compared to the academicians.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The **German National Academy of Sciences Leopoldina** (German: *Deutsche Akademie der Naturforscher Leopoldina – Nationale Akademie der Wissenschaften*), in short **Leopoldina**, is the national academy of Germany, and is located in Halle (Saale).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Founded on 1 January 1652, based on academic models in Italy, it was originally named the *Academia Naturae Curiosorum* until 1687 when Emperor Leopold I raised it to an academy and named it after himself.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] It was since known under the German name *Deutsche Akademie der Naturforscher Leopoldina* until 2007, when it was declared to be Germany's National Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The archives of Leopoldina are some of the oldest in the world based on the fact that the records date back to the 17th century.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] These records provide a window into the German sciences of the last 350 years.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] In 1670, the society began to publish the *Ephemeriden* or *Miscellanea Curiosa*, one of the earliest scientific journals and one which had a particularly strong focus on medicine and related aspects of natural philosophy, such as botany and physiology., pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] 7–8 It was recognized by Emperor Leopold I who raised it to an academy in 1677, and then declared it an Imperial Academy in 1687, naming it **Sacri Romani Imperii Academia Caesareo-Leopoldina Naturae Curiosorum** and allowing it to carry his name.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] At first, the society conducted its business by correspondence and was located wherever the president was working., pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] 8–9 After Schweinfurt, the Academy was rooted in many places before it was permanently located in Halle in 1878.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Following Schweinfurt in chronological order: Nuremberg, Augsburg, Altdorf, Erfurt, Halle, Nuremberg, Erlangen, Bonn, Breslau (currently Wrocław, Poland), Jena, Dresden, and finally Halle., pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] There were many efforts during years of national prosperity to elevate the Academy to the status of a 'national institute,' but all such early efforts failed.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] In those times the Academy was not on the nation's agenda at a political or academic level.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Later, however, its members began to enrich the Academy with an obligation to be present at its proceedings so as to improve their public standing.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Thus they began to hold regular monthly meetings, even in the challenging conditions of 1924,, pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] 8–9 which had to be attended by all local members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] When Adolf Hitler became Germany's Chancellor in 1933, the Leopoldina started to exclude its Jewish members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Albert Einstein was the first victim because of public pressure.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Eight of them were murdered by the Nazis over the course of World War II.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Nevertheless, the Leopoldina did not suffer as much influence from the Nazi regime as other German academies, thanks to the president of the Leopoldina at the time, Emil Abderhalden.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Abderhalden resisted Nazi pressure by reorganizing Sections of the Academy and introducing a new series 'Biographies of German Natural Scientists' in 1932.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] After World War II, Halle became part of East Germany.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] During this time, the German Democratic Republic shut down all societies, leading the members of the Leopoldina to meet unofficially and in private.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Efforts were made to reestablish the Academy, however.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] An edition of Goethe's 'The Works of Science' began to be edited under the Academy's name in 1947, and lectures started again in 1948.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] However, the Academy was not officially reopened until 1952.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] This reopening came just in time for the Academy to celebrate its tercentenary.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] After reopening, the Leopoldina successfully resisted attempts from the German Democratic Republic to reconstitute the Academy as a specifically East German institute and continued to think of itself as an institution for the whole of Germany.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] This was greatly affected by the building of the Berlin Wall in August 1961.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The Academy was able to stay independent of national politics, which allowed it to bridge East and West Germany through scientific ideas.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] In 1991, after German reunification, the Leopoldina was granted the status of a non-profit organisation.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] It is funded jointly by the German government and the government of the state of Saxony-Anhalt., pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] 10–14 A new section was also created for the history of culture with the emphasis on medicine and the natural sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] As the German Academy of Sciences, it is a counterpart to the rights and responsibilities of institutions such as Britain's Royal Society and the United States' National Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] As the national academy, the Leopoldina will act as a consulting service on matters of science and science related policy for the German government, including parliament and social and political organizations.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The Leopoldina is the first and foremost academic society in Germany to advise the German government on a variety of scientific matters, for instance on climate change and disease control.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The Leopoldina gives conferences and lectures and continues to publish the *Ephemeriden* under the name *Nova Acta Leopoldina*.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] It issues various medals and awards, offers grants and scholarships and elects new members to itself.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The Academy also maintains a library and an archive and it also researches its own history and publishes another journal, *Acta Historica Leopoldina* devoted to this subject., pp.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Consistently with its national preeminence, it also collaborates extensively with other learned societies in international exchanges of ideas and policy recommendations.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Details of such initiatives are included on its multilingual website.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Three quarters of the members are from German-speaking countries (Germany, Austria, Switzerland) and one quarter from about 30 other nations.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The election to membership of the Leopoldina is the highest academic honour awarded by an institution in Germany.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Some laureates are also fellows of the Leopoldina.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Members might also attribute discoveries and success to the academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] For example, the asteroid 893 Leopoldina is named in its honour.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] At the head of the Academy there is a Presidium, elected by the Senate, consisting of the President, acting as the chair, four Vice Presidents, and other members at large.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] These position terms are five years long and can only be held twice by the same person.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The Senate of the Academy currently consists of 39 members representing different sections and disciplines of science, as well as representatives from Switzerland and Austria.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] Senate members serve for four years and can only be re-elected once.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-leopoldina] The latest President of the Academy, Gerald Haug, from Berlin, became the Academy's 27th president when he took office on 1 March 2020.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-republic-of-tajikistan] Originally a part of the Soviet Academy of Sciences, the Tajik Academy of Sciences was established in 1951 as the **Academy of Sciences of Tajik SSR**, designated the highest scientific body in Tajik SSR and since 1991 in the Republic of Tajikistan.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The **Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union** was the highest scientific institution of the Soviet Union from 1925 to 1991.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] It united the country's leading scientists and was subordinated directly to the Council of Ministers of the Soviet Union (until 1946 the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1991, by the decree of the President of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic, the Russian Academy of Sciences was established on the basis of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In the first years of Soviet Russia, the Institute of the Academy of Sciences was perceived rather ambiguously as a closed and elite scientific education.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] However, in 1918, after negotiations with the then leadership of the Academy of Sciences, which had already been renamed from "Imperial" to "Russian", cooperation began with the new government.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The financing of the academy was entrusted to the People's Commissariat for Education and the Central Commission for the Improvement of the Life of Scientists.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1925, its 200th anniversary was solemnly celebrated.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] A new charter was adopted for this date.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The first president of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was the well-known scientist, geologist Alexander Karpinsky, who previously held the presidency of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Attempts to establish state and party control over the previously independent Academy began in the mid-1920s: in 1925 the academy was subordinated to the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1928, under pressure from the authorities, a number of new Communist members were elected to it.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In January 1929, the academicians defiantly failed the three Communist candidates, Vladimir Fritsche, Nikolai Lukin and Abram Deborin, who were running for the Academy of Sciences, but already in February, under conditions of extreme pressure, they were forced to reconsider their decision.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1929, a government commission headed by Yuri Petrovich Figatner was sent to Leningrad to "cleanse" the academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In June–December 1929, by its decision, 128 full-time employees (out of 960) and 520 supernumerals (out of 830) were dismissed from the Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Sergey Oldenburg was removed from the post of the permanent secretary of the academy at the end of October 1929, defending her independence.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] After that, the party-state bodies established full control over the academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] A new Presidium of the Academy of Sciences was elected.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Even before this, on February 25, 1929, the Politburo issued a special decision: to leave Alexander Karpinsky as president, Gleb Krzhizhanovsky, Nikolai Marr, and Vladimir Komarov as vice-presidents, and Vyacheslav Volgin as the permanent secretary.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Thus, for the first time in the practice of the Academy of Sciences, its leading core was directively appointed at a meeting of the highest party body with subsequent automatic approval at the General Assembly, and this also became a precedent for subsequent practice.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] During the period from December 1929 to December 1930, over 100 people were arrested under the "Academic Case" (mainly experts in the humanities, primarily historians).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In February – April 1930, a new charter of the Academy of Sciences was developed and approved.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The development of the project was entrusted to an academic commission approved by the plenary session of the Committee for the Management of Scientists and Educational Institutions of the Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union, headed by Vyacheslav Volgin.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The first meeting of the commission to draw up a charter and reorganize the Academy of Sciences was held on February 28, 1930.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The draft of the new charter was discussed and approved by the session of the Academy of Sciences on March 31 – April 5, 1930, and it approved the first work plan of the Academy of Sciences for 1931–1932.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] On April 4, 1930, the charter was adopted at the General Assembly.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1930, in connection with the reorganization of the Soviet government, the Academy of Sciences was transferred to the Central Executive Committee of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1934, the Presidium of the academy and 14 scientific institutes were transferred from Leningrad (formerly and now St.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Petersburg) to Moscow (On April 25, 1934, Vyacheslav Molotov signed the corresponding decree of the Council of People's Commissars of the Soviet Union).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] As Felix Perchenok noted, "the transfer of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union to Moscow – one of the most important steps towards turning it into the headquarters of Soviet science – was carried out in a fire order".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1935, the permanent secretary of the academy, Vyacheslav Volgin, wrote a letter to Joseph Stalin asking for his release from the position of permanent secretary.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In the letter, he stressed that he alone was doing the difficult work of an indispensable secretary all the time, while other members of the party group only "threw out ideas", sometimes useful, sometimes fantastic.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] For five years in this post, Volgin not only could not continue his scientific work, but could not even read books in his specialty, could not follow the development of his science.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] "Meanwhile", he adds, "I was considered in the well-known narrow field as the best expert on the subject".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] "I'm already 56 years old", Vyacheslav Petrovich continues, "and there is not much time left for science.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] A few more years – and I will not be able to return to science".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Moreover, in a letter to Stalin, he noted that in the party group, he no longer feels the former positive assessment of his work.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] On August 8, 1935, at a meeting of the Politburo, it was proposed to release Vyacheslav Volgin from the post of permanent secretary of the academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] On November 20, 1935, by resolution of the general meeting of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, he was thanked for his work in the governing bodies of the Academy of Sciences and freed from the duties of an indispensable secretary.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] His place was taken by the former affairs manager of the Council of People's Commissars Nikolai Gorbunov.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] By the decree of the Presidium of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union dated June 26, 1937, this position was abolished altogether, and since that time administrative officers have performed the duties of secretaries.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] From 1945 to 1970, the total number of researchers (including faculty and research personnel of higher education) increased more than sevenfold: from 130 thousand to 950 thousand people.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] One of the notable figures of this time was the economist Lev Gatovsky, which became director of the Institute of Economics of the academy from 1965 to 1971.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1980 and 1985, the total number of research workers was already 1.4 and 1.5 million, respectively.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The total number of scientific, scientific, pedagogical, design and design organizations of various types from 1945 to 1985 also increased steadily and amounted in the Soviet Union as a whole to 1,700, 5,300, and 5,100 successively in 1945, 1970 and 1985.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] For its achievements, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was twice awarded the Order of Lenin: in 1969 and 1974.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1932, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union organized its first branches – the Ural and the Far East – and research bases – the Kazakh and Tajik.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1933, the Transcaucasian branch was established with branches in Armenia and Azerbaijan, and in 1934, the Kola Research Base.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1935, Azerbaijan, and in 1936 the Armenian branch of the Transcaucasian branch were transformed into independent branches of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1936, the Northern Base appeared, in 1939 the Uzbek Base, and in 1941, on the eve of the Great Patriotic War, the Turkmen branch.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] By the end of 1941, the Academy of Sciences had 7 branches (Azerbaijan, Armenian, Kazakh, Tajik, Turkmen, Uzbek, and Ural), two research bases (Kola and North), and one mountain taiga station.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The scientific institutions of the branches and bases of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union at that time had about 1,500 scientific and technical workers, including 12 academicians, 11 corresponding members, 126 doctors, 284 candidates of science, 610 scientists without a scientific degree.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In connection with the collapse of the Soviet Union, the scientific institutions of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, located in the former Soviet republics and which were part of the academies of sciences of the Union republics, became part of the new independent states.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In fact, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union was the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In December 1991, elections to the Russian Academy of Sciences were held, and the scientists who took part in these elections, together with the full members of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, constituted the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] In 1992, the International Association of Academies of Sciences was established.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The objectives of the activities of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union were to promote the full implementation of scientific advances in the practice of communist construction in the USSR; identification and development of the most important and fundamental areas of science.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Coordination was also conducted through regional offices and republican academies of sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The research activity of the academy was conducted in a network of institutes, laboratories, observatories.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The network of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union included 295 scientific institutions.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union had its own publishing house, a research fleet, a network of libraries.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union awarded awards to scientists who have made significant contributions to the development of science.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] On 1 January 1936 the Academy of Sciences had 98 active members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The organs of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union were formed exclusively on an electoral basis.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] The supreme body is the General Meeting of Academicians and Corresponding Members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] To guide the academy in the periods between sessions of the General Assembly, it elects every 4 years the Presidium of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-the-soviet-union] Critics noted that, despite the broadest powers and formal responsibility for the state and development of all science in the Soviet Union, during its existence, the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union did not come up with any serious project reforming Soviet science.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The **Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan** (Turkmen: *Türkmenistanyň Ylymlar akademiýasy*) is a state body in Turkmenistan founded in 1951, which is responsible for the implementation of Turkmen scientific and technical policy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The academy was closed under president Saparmurat Niyazov and reopened by his successor, Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] This work is organized in five institutes: "1.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The Magtymguly National Institute of Language, Literature and Manuscripts 2.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] Institute of Seismology and Atmospheric Physics.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The academy pursues research in six priority areas: "1.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] Nanotechnology, chemical technology, new materials research and energy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] Biotechnology, molecular biology, agriculture, ecology and genetics.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] Information and telecommunication systems, computer technology.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] Modern medicine and drug production technologies.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The academy publishes four journals, *Наука и техника в Туркменистане* (Science and Technology in Turkmenistan), *Проблемы освоения пустынь* (Problems of Desert Development), *Мирас* (Heritage), and *Наука и техника молодёжи* (Science and Technology for Youth).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The academy's lineage dates back to the Turkmen Scientific Commission, founded in 1922.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] It would later become the State Academic Council, under the People's Commissariat of Education, and then in May 1932 the Turkmen Scientific Research Institute.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] In March 1936, by resolution of the Central Executive Committee and the Council of People's Commissars of the Turkmen Soviet Socialist Republic, it was reduced to the Institute of History and Language and Literature.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] In 1941, the Turkmen Branch of the USSR Academy of Sciences was founded.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] By 1945, research staff included thirty-five Turkmens.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The present academy was established 29 June 1951 by decree of the Presidium of the USSR Supreme Soviet.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] By 1986, the academy had 15 research institutions.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] In the summer of 1998, the academy came under the direct control of the president of Turkmenistan.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] It was closed for more than 10 years and was reopened by President Niyazov's successor, Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] With the revival of the academy in 2009 the structure of science and research in Turkmenistan changed, reflecting reforms initiated by President Berdimuhamedow.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] With the new structure of the academy, research is centralized.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] The academy was restored according to presidential resolution number 10458 dated June 12, 2009, "On the question about the Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] According to the resolution, 11 institutes and three organisations serving the science sector were moved: the library, the printing house and the Ylym publishing house.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/academy-of-sciences-of-turkmenistan] By decree of President Berdimuhamedow in January 2019, the government will gradually end state funding of the Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan, phasing it out over three years.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had two brothers Vasily (1904) and Andrei (1911) and a sister Tatyana (1908) (two born sisters died in infancy).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] His father (Nikolai Vasilyevich Nesmeyanov), graduated with excellence Vladimir Gymnasium, and then the Faculty of Law of Moscow University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He became interested in enlightenment and was working as a public teacher in the village of Bushov (Tula province) for 10 years.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had married in 1898 and worked at the Moscow city government, then he was a director Bakhrushinsky orphanage in Moscow (1901 – 1917).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander's mother, Lyudmila Danilovna (1878 – 1958), was a multi-talented teacher.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] At ten years Alexander became a vegetarian, and in 1913 he stopped eating fish.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] It was not easy to follow this conviction, especially in the famine years of 1918 – 1921, when roach and herring were an essential food product.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had become interested in various branches of biology: entomology, hydrobiology, ornithology and from the age of thirteen became interested in chemistry.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Strakhov's private Moscow gymnasium, which he graduated with honors.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1917, he entered the natural department of the Faculty of Physics and Mathematics at Moscow University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] There were no entrance exams due to the passage of the revolution.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Studying in this difficult time required great self-sacrifice and fanatical dedication.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] They studied in unheated rooms and there was not enough laboratory equipment.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Transport was bad, and sometimes Alexander had to walk on foot to the university from Sokolniki.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1920, classes at Moscow State University were frozen due to problems with heating, and Nesmeyanov entered the Military Pedagogical Academy on Bolshaya Gruzinskaya Street.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the same time, he worked in the laboratories of the Shanyavsky Moscow City People's University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] By the end of 1920, Alexander Nikolayevich returned to studies at the academy and at Moscow University, where heating had already been restored.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He meets the "future scientific mentor", Professor N.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] While he was working as a night watchman at the faculty, Nesmeyanov lived in the laboratory of N.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Zelinsky and devoting all his time to scientific experiments.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] After graduating from the university (1922), Nesmeyanov remained at the department of Academician N.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He held the positions of assistant (1924–1938), associate professor, professor (since 1935).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He headed the Department of Organic Chemistry at the Institute of Fine Chemical Technology since 1938.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] From 1939 to 1954 Nesmeyanov was director of the Institute of Organic Chemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1939 he was elected as a corresponding member of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, and in 1943 - an academician of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1946 - 1951 he was an Academician-Secretary of the Department of Chemical Sciences of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the end of the Great Patriotic War, Alexander Nikolayevich returned to his native university.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He headed the Department of Organic Chemistry (1944 – 1958), he was the dean of the Faculty of Chemistry (1944 – 1948), and then became the rector of Moscow State University(1948 – 1951).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thanks to Nesmeyanov's research in the field of organometallic compounds during the war and post-war years, a number of important results were obtained that are of great theoretical and practical importance.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] These studies were aimed at developing methods for the synthesis and studying the chemical properties of various representatives of an important and extensive class of compounds located at the junction of inorganic and organic chemistry.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] During the period of Nesmeyanov's rectorship, the construction of a large complex of university buildings on the Sparrow (Lenin) Hills began.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Under his leadership, competent commissions were created to develop technical specifications for the placement of university units in a new location.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] They worked in close creative contact with the author's group of architects (full members of the Academy of Architecture of the USSR L.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Simultaneously with the colossal construction, the development of the university structure is taking place, and curricula are being improved.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thus, courses on the history of sciences were introduced into the curricula of the natural faculties.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1948, the Faculty of Biology was reorganized into the Faculty of Biology and Soil.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1949 construction began on an agrobiological station in Chashnikovo.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the same time, the Faculty of Geology was created and the departments were organized: crystallography and crystal chemistry; history of geological sciences.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1950, assistance was provided to the University of Chisinau with literature and equipment.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1951, after the death of the President of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, S.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Vavilov Nesmeyanov was summoned to a member of the Politburo of the Central Committee, G.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] On February 16, 1951, at an extraordinary session of the general meeting of the Academy of Sciences, Nesmeyanov was elected its president.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1952, he founded the Institute for Scientific Information.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1954, he opened the Institute of Organoelement Compounds of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, which he led until his death (at present, the institute bears the name of A.N.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] On May 19, 1961, Nesmeyanov resigned as president of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union of his own free will.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In May 1969, at a meeting of the Academic Council of the Institute of Organoelement Compounds, Nesmeyanov spoke out against being elected a senior researcher Candidate of Chemical Sciences Rokhlin, stating “I am a vindictive person.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Last year, Rokhlin was among those who, at an institute rally, spoke out against the introduction of Soviet troops into Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] This speech did not affect the results of the vote, and Rokhlin was elected a senior researcher.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Deputy of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR 3-5 convocations (1950 – 1962).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was one of the academicians of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, who in 1973 signed a letter from scientists to the Pravda newspaper condemning "the behavior of Academician A.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In the letter, Sakharov was accused of having "made a number of statements discrediting the state system, the foreign and domestic policy of the Soviet Union", and academicians assessed his human rights activities as "defaming the honor and dignity of the Soviet scientist".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was interested in literature and painting, wrote poetry, sketches, was an avid mushroom picker.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was buried in Moscow at the Novodevichy Cemetery.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The first wife – Nina Vladimirovna Koperina (1900–1986) – is a chemist, she has worked at Moscow State University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Children from the first marriage: Olga (1930–2014) – candidate of chemical sciences; Nikolai (1932–1992) – Doctor of Chemical Sciences, Professor я.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The second wife – Vinogradova Marina Anatolyevna (1921–2013) – is a philologist and a writer.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Nesmeyanov had two brothers and a sister: Andrey Nesmeyanov (1911–1983) – radiochemist, head of the radiochemistry department of Moscow State University, professor, corresponding member of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Vasily Nesmeyanov (1904–1941) – worked as deputy head of the Topographic and Geodetic Service of the Main Directorate of Geodesy and Cartography under the Council of People's Commissars of the USSR.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was shot on July 28, 1941 on charges of espionage.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was rehabilitated on September 17, 1955 by the decision of the Military Collegium of the Supreme Court of the USSR.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander Nikolayevich was one of the greatest organic chemists of the 20th century.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He organised a number of fundamental works on the theory of the structure and reactivity of organic compounds.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He created a new discipline lying on the border of inorganic and organic chemistry, which was called "chemistry of organoelement compounds".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Also he has researched the production of synthetic food, the creation of new drugs and the synthesis of a number of technical materials.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Studying the decomposition of double salts of aryldiazonium halides with mercury halides by copper powder, in 1929 Nesmeyanov proposed a new method for obtaining arylmercury halides.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Later, the diazo method was extended to the synthesis of organometallic compounds of thallium, germanium, tin, lead, arsenic, antimony, and bismuth.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The features of the diazo method, which distinguish it from direct metalation methods, are the possibility of obtaining organometallic compounds with different functional groups in the carbon radical and the possibility of selectively introducing a metal atom into a certain position.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1935 – 1948, Nesmeyanov, together with K.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Kocheshkov, obtained organic derivatives of tin, lead, antimony and other metals.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Due to mutual transitions from organic derivatives of some elements to organic compounds of other elements, organometallic compounds obtained by the diazo method have found new applications in synthesis.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The study by Nesmeyanov of the products of the addition of mercuric chloride to ethylene, acetylene and their derivatives led to the concept of the “dual reactivity” of a substance and the “transfer of the reaction center” along the chain π, π-, σ, π-, σ, σ- and p,π-conjugations in a molecule.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Further research showed that these phenomena are fundamentally different from tautomerism.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] With the participation of his colleague A.E.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Borisov, Nesmeyanov formulated the rule according to which electrophilic and homolytic substitution at the olefin carbon atom occurs with the preservation of the geometric configuration (Nesmeyanov – Borisov rule).
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thanks to his research, which showed the enolate structure of ketone derivatives with alkali metals and magnesium, that is, the existence of O-derivatives of ketones, Nesmeyanov refuted Knorr 's concept of "pseudomerism ".
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In the study of the structure of mercury b-, lead- and organotin derivatives of nitrosophenols, Nesmeyanov discovered the phenomenon of metallotropy, that is, a special tautomerism in which a reversible transfer of an organometallic group occurs.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Lutsenko discovered heteroatomic tautomerism (between carbon and oxygen atoms) in keto-enol systems of tin, o- and germanium compounds.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Ustynyuk, discovered a new type of metallotropy: it was found that in fluorenylchromium tricarbonyl anions, η 6 -complexes are equilibrium and reversibly isomerized into η 5 -complexes.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1954, research into the chemistry of ferrocene began at the Department of Organic Chemistry at Moscow State University and at INEOS under the direction of Nesmeyanov.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] It turned out that the functional derivatives of ferrocene react similarly to aromatic compounds.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] However, it has been shown that the electronic effects of the substituents are transmitted through the metallocene core by an inductive mechanism, and therefore have a lesser effect than on benzene derivatives.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Research on ferrocene and its derivatives made it possible to create a number of photosensitive compositions that allow obtaining a stable image on paper, fabric, plastics and metals, and also led to the creation of a new drug, ferrocerone, which fights diseases associated with iron deficiency.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] On the basis of cymantrene, Nesmeyanov proposed a new antiknock agent for motor gasoline.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Rybinskaya, developed a method for the synthesis of various five- and six-membered heterocycles, which is based on the high activity of carbonyl groups and the mobility of the β-substituent in compounds of the type RCOCH=CHX.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The same group of scientists developed the method of "β-ketovinylation", which consists in introducing an RCOCH=CH group into the molecule.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The reaction of β-substituted vinyl ketones with an azide ion made it possible to study the stereochemistry and propose a mechanism for nucleophilic substitution at the activated double bond.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In collaboration with other scientists, Nesmeyanov carried out a number of works in the field of radical telomerization and rearrangement radicals.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In addition to studies of already known reactions, thermal telomerization of ethylene and propylene with silicon hydrides has been developed and other new telomerization reactions.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Also, new routes for the synthesis of compounds containing groups such as CCl3, CCl3CHCl, CCl3C<, CCl 2=CH, CCl2=CHX and others.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The study of compounds containing the CCl3-C=C< group showed the rearrangement during reactions with attack on the terminal atoms of the system, which confirmed the presence of σ,π-conjugation.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Kost discovered the chain radical isomerization of CCl3CBr=CH2 to CCl2=CClCH2Br under ultraviolet illumination.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In continuation of the work related to the previously created diazo method, Nesmeyanov and L.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Makarova investigated the mechanism of decomposition of aryldiazonium and diaryliodonium salts.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] This made it possible to synthesize new types of onium compounds - diphenylbromonium, diphenylchloronium and triphenyloxonium salts.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Tolstaya and other scientists, Nesmeyanov showed that double salts of diphenylbromonium and diphenylchloronium halides with heavy metal halides are decomposed by powders of the corresponding metals with the formation of organometallic compounds.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thus, the diazo method began to be used to obtain σ-aryl complexes of transition metals and other organometallic compounds.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1961, Nesmeyanov formulated the idea of obtaining food by synthetic methods, bypassing agriculture.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Berthelot, as well as an awareness of the modern possibilities of organic synthesis, the problems of preserving the environment and the efficiency of food production.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] The main areas of work were: the development of highly efficient methods for obtaining nutrients; reproduction of the appearance, taste, smell, color, shape, consistency and other properties of natural products in synthetic food substances.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] As a result of research at INEOS, processes have been developed for obtaining black caviar, new forms of potato products, pasta and cereals and combined meat products based on vegetable and animal proteins.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander Nikolayevich's work on the chemistry of organoelement compounds brought him fame and recognition not only in the Soviet Union, but also in the world.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was elected an honorary member of several dozen foreign national academies and scientific societies.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:alexander-nesmeyanov/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
